<!-- Begin Title -->
<h1>Golden Ratio</h1>
<!-- End Title -->
<hr class=3D"margin-t-1-8 margin-b-3-4">
<!-- Begin Total Content -->
<div class=3D"attachments text-align-r">
<a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/notebooks/Constants/GoldenRatio.nb=
" download=3D"GoldenRatio.nb"><img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/entries/download-notebook-icon.png" width=3D"26" height=3D"27" alt=3D"D=
OWNLOAD Mathematica Notebook"><span>Download <span class=3D"display-i displ=
ay-n__600">Wolfram&nbsp;</span>Notebook</span></a>
</div>
<!-- Begin Content -->
<div class=3D"entry-content">
<p>
The golden ratio, also known as the divine proportion, golden mean, or gold=
en section, is a number often encountered when taking the ratios of distanc=
es in simple geometric
 figures such as the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Pentagon.html=
">pentagon</a>, <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Pentagram.html">pe=
ntagram</a>,
 <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Decagon.html">decagon</a> and <a =
href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Dodecahedron.html">dodecahedron</a>.
 It is denoted <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/G=
oldenRatio/Inline1.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">,
 or sometimes <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Go=
ldenRatio/Inline2.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"tau">.
</p>
<p>
The designations "phi" (for the absolute value of the <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRatioConjugate.html">golden ratio conjugate</a> <=
img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inlin=
e3.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" bo=
rder=3D"0" width=3D"29" height=3D"21" alt=3D"1/phi">)
 and "Phi" (for the larger quantity <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.c=
om/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline4.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=
=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" =
alt=3D"phi">) are sometimes also used (Knott), although this usage is
 not necessarily recommended.
</p>
<p>
The term "golden section" (in German, <i>goldener Schnitt</i> or <i>der gol=
dene Schnitt</i>) seems to first have been used by Martin Ohm in the 1835 2=
nd
 edition of his textbook <i>Die Reine Elementar-Mathematik</i> (Livio 2002,=
 p.&nbsp;6).
 The first known use of this term in English is in James Sulley's 1875 arti=
cle on
 aesthetics in the 9th edition of the <i>Encyclopedia Britannica.</i> The s=
ymbol <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRati=
o/Inline5.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:1=
00%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi"> ("phi") was appare=
ntly first
 used by Mark Barr at the beginning of the 20th century in commemoration of=
 the Greek
 sculptor Phidias (ca. 490-430 BC), who a number of art historians claim ma=
de extensive
 use of the golden ratio in his works (Livio 2002, pp.&nbsp;5-6). Similarly=
, the alternate
 notation <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Golden=
Ratio/Inline6.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-wid=
th:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"8" height=3D"21" alt=3D"tau">
 is an abbreviation of the Greek <i>tome</i>, meaning "to cut."
</p>
<p>
<img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inli=
ne7.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" b=
order=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi"> has surprising connectio=
ns with <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ContinuedFraction.html">co=
ntinued fractions</a> and the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Eucl=
ideanAlgorithm.html">Euclidean
 algorithm</a> for computing the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/G=
reatestCommonDivisor.html">greatest common
 divisor</a> of two <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Integer.html">=
integers</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"339.927" src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/eps-svg/GoldenRatio_1401.svg" class=3D" w=
olfram-c2c-wrapper mathworld-c2c_above" alt=3D"GoldenRatio" data-c2c-file=
=3D"/mathcode/GoldenRatioRectangle.txt" data-c2c-type=3D"text/html" id=3D"m=
athworld-c2c_above-0">
</div>
<p>
Given a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Rectangle.html">rectangle<=
/a> having sides in the ratio <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ima=
ges/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline8.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max=
-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"31" height=3D"21" alt=3D=
"1:x">, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRa=
tio/Inline9.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width=
:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 is defined as the unique number <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/=
images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline10.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D=
"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"x"> such that partitioning the original <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wo=
lfram.com/Rectangle.html">rectangle</a>
 into a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Square.html">square</a> an=
d new <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Rectangle.html">rectangle</a=
>
 as illustrated above results in a new <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram=
.com/Rectangle.html">rectangle</a> which
 also has sides in the ratio <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/imag=
es/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline11.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max=
-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"31" height=3D"21" alt=3D=
"1:x"> (i.e., such that the yellow rectangles shown above are similar).
 Such a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Rectangle.html">rectangle<=
/a> is called a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GoldenRectangle.ht=
ml">golden
 rectangle</a>, and successive points dividing a <a href=3D"https://mathwor=
ld.wolfram.com/GoldenRectangle.html">golden
 rectangle</a> into <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Square.html">s=
quares</a> lie on a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/LogarithmicSpi=
ral.html">logarithmic
 spiral</a>, giving a figure known as a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfra=
m.com/Whirl.html">whirling square</a>.
</p>
<p>
Based on the above definition, it can immediately be seen that
