Triangle.html">isosceles triangle</a> with a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.w=
olfram.com/VertexAngle.html">vertex angle</a> of <img src=3D"https://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline23.svg" class=3D"inlinef=
ormula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"28" =
height=3D"21" alt=3D"36 degrees">) are in a golden ratio to its base and, i=
n fact,
 this was the method used by Pythagoras to construct <img src=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline24.svg" class=3D"inl=
ineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"=
9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">. The ratio of the <a href=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/Circumradius.html">circumradius</a>
 to the length of the side of a <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/De=
cagon.html">decagon</a> is also <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/i=
mages/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline25.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"phi">,
</p>
