s/GoldenRatio/Inline83.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"106" height=3D"22" alt=3D"[a_0;a_1,=
a_2,...]"> and let the denominators of the convergents
 be denoted <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Gold=
enRatio/Inline84.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-=
width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"22" alt=3D"q_1">,
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inl=
ine85.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%"=
 border=3D"0" width=3D"16" height=3D"22" alt=3D"q_2">, ..., <img src=3D"htt=
ps://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline86.svg" class=
=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" wi=
dth=3D"16" height=3D"22" alt=3D"q_n">. As can be seen from the plots above,=
 the regularity in
 the continued fraction of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images=
/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline87.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-h=
eight:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"ph=
i">
 means that <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Gold=
enRatio/Inline88.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-=
width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 is one of a set of numbers of measure 0 whose continued fraction sequences=
 <i>do
 not</i> converge to <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/KhinchinsCons=
tant.html">Khinchin's constant</a> or
 the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/LevyConstant.html">L=C3=A9vy =
constant</a>.
</p>
<p>
The golden ratio has <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EngelExpansio=
n.html">Engel expansion</a> 1, 2, 5,
6, 13, 16, 16, 38, 48, 58, 104, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A02825=
9">A028259</a>).
</p>
<div class=3D"center-image">
<img style=3D"max-width:100%;max-height:100%;" width=3D"447.211" src=3D"htt=
