t/html">
</div>
<p>
Steinhaus (1999, pp.&nbsp;48-49) considers the distribution of the <a href=
=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/FractionalPart.html">fractional parts</a>=
 of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/=
Inline89.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:10=
0%" border=3D"0" width=3D"22" height=3D"21" alt=3D"nphi">
 in the intervals bounded by 0, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/i=
mages/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline90.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"=
max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"29" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"1/n">, <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Golde=
nRatio/Inline91.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-w=
idth:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"29" height=3D"21" alt=3D"2/n">,
 ..., <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRati=
o/Inline92.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:=
100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"67" height=3D"21" alt=3D"(n-1)/n">,
 1, and notes that they are much more uniformly distributed than would be e=
xpected
 due to chance (i.e., <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equa=
tions/GoldenRatio/Inline93.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height=
:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"64" height=3D"21" alt=3D"frac(n=
phi)">
 is close to an <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EquidistributedSeq=
uence.html">equidistributed sequence</a>).
 In particular, the number of empty intervals for <img src=3D"https://mathw=
orld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline94.svg" class=3D"inline=
formula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"39"=
 height=3D"21" alt=3D"n=3D1">, 2, ..., are a mere 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 0, 1, 0, 2=
, 0, 1, 1,
 0, 2, 2, ... (OEIS <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A036414">A036414</a>). The v=
alues of
 <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inl=
ine95.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%"=
 border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"n"> for which <i>no</i> bins=
 are left blank
 are then given by 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 8, 10, 13, 16, 21, 34, 55, 89, 144, ..=
. (OEIS
 <a href=3D"http://oeis.org/A036415">A036415</a>). Steinhaus (1983) remarks=
 that the
 highly uniform distribution has its roots in the <a href=3D"https://mathwo=
rld.wolfram.com/ContinuedFraction.html">continued
 fraction</a> for <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equation=
s/GoldenRatio/Inline96.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" height=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">.
</p>
<p>
The sequence <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Gol=
denRatio/Inline97.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max=
-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"70" height=3D"21" alt=3D"{frac(x^n)}">,
 of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PowerFractionalParts.html">pow=
er fractional parts</a>, where <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/im=
ages/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline98.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"m=
ax-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"51" height=3D"21" alt=
=3D"frac(x)"> is the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/FractionalPar=
t.html">fractional part</a>,
 is <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/EquidistributedSequence.html">=
equidistributed</a> for <i>almost all</i>
 real numbers <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations/Go=
ldenRatio/Inline99.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100%;ma=
x-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"37" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x&gt;1">,
 with the golden ratio being one exception.
</p>
<p>
Salem showed that the set of <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Pisot=
Number.html">Pisot numbers</a> is closed, with <img src=3D"https://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/images/equations/GoldenRatio/Inline100.svg" class=3D"inlinefo=
rmula" style=3D"max-height:100%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"9" he=
ight=3D"21" alt=3D"phi">
 the smallest accumulation point of the set (Le Lionnais 1983).
</p>
<p>
The real root of <img src=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/images/equations=
/GoldenRatio/Inline101.svg" class=3D"inlineformula" style=3D"max-height:100=
%;max-width:100%" border=3D"0" width=3D"109" height=3D"21" alt=3D"x^3-x^2-1=
=3D0">
 is sometimes known as the <a href=3D"https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Supergo=
ldenRatio.html">supergolden ratio</a>.
</p>
<p>
In the Season 1 episode "<a href=3D"http://www.tv.com/sabotage/episode/3985=
96/summary.html">Sabotage</a>" (2005) of the television crime drama <i><a h=
ref=3D"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/B000ERVJKE/ref=3Dnosim/ericst=
reasuretro">NUMB3RS</a></i>,
 math genius Charlie Eppes mentions that the golden ratio is found in the p=
yramids
 of Giza and the Parthenon at Athens. Similarly, the character Robert Langd=
on in the
 novel <i><a href=3D"http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/1400079179/ref=
=3Dnosim/ericstreasuretro">The
 Da Vinci Code</a></i> makes similar such statements (Brown 2003, pp.&nbsp;=
93-95).
 However, claims of the significance of the golden ratio appearing prominen=
tly in
 art, architecture, sculpture, anatomy, etc., tend to be greatly exaggerate=
d.
</p>
